<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="91" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">
the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carsidaridae" genus="Mesohomotoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesohomotoma" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mesohomotoma</taxonomicName>
Kuwayama was reviewed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hollis, D" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Entomology Series" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="87 - 127" title="A review of the Malvales-feeding psyllid family Carsidaridae (Homoptera)." volume="56" year="1987">Hollis (1987)</bibRefCitation>
. The species included in the genus have a lot of variation between populations, and subtle differences between species. Although 
<bibRefCitation author="Hollis, D" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Entomology Series" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="87 - 127" title="A review of the Malvales-feeding psyllid family Carsidaridae (Homoptera)." volume="56" year="1987">Hollis (1987)</bibRefCitation>
suspected all nominal taxa may represent a single species, he did not formally synonymise them, recommending that further research into their biology and hostplants be undertaken to further investigate species boundaries in the genus. This species breeds in the tips of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Hibiscus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Hibiscus tiliaceus" order="Malvales" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tiliaceus">Hibiscus tiliaceus</taxonomicName>
branches. The nymphs produce filamentous exudates, which forms a woolly coating on the leaves and stem of the plant (Figure 21). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carsidaridae" genus="Mesohomotoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesohomotoma hibisci" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hibisci">Mesohomotoma hibisci</taxonomicName>
is considered a pest (
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="91">David Hockings 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
